Every man's life gets renovated a few times without his permission. The job that ended. The marriage that ended. The kid who just left for college, or the one who just arrived and rearranged everything. The retirement you looked forward to that feels strangely like a demotion. The birthday that made the math of your life suddenly feel real.

From the outside, some transitions even look like wins. From the inside, they all ask the same unsettling question: *who am I now?*

## What's actually going on

Men build identity out of function — provider, husband, dad, the guy who's good at his job. It's honest scaffolding, but it means every major transition threatens more than logistics. When the role changes, the man holding it can feel like he's disappearing. That's why a job loss can flatten a strong man, why new fathers can feel lost in their own house, and why success transitions — promotion, retirement, the move you wanted — can still bring a low-grade grief nobody warned you about.

Unprocessed, that grief tends to leak: irritability, withdrawal, drinking a little more, working strange hours, picking fights. Processed, it becomes something else entirely — raw material.

## How counseling helps

First, stabilization: getting your feet under you in the season you're actually in, not the one that ended. Then the deeper work: grieving honestly what's gone (men are allowed to do that, despite the rumors), sorting what was scaffolding from what was actually you, and deciding — on purpose — what the next chapter is being built around.

This is where the narrative work I do earns its keep. A transition is a chapter break, and chapter breaks are where stories get redirected. Men leave this work not just recovered, but re-aimed.

## When to reach out

If a chapter has ended — or is about to — and you notice you're not quite you, don't wait until the drift becomes a rut. The middle of a transition is exactly the right time to talk to someone.
